We can hardly help suspecting that, with his strong dislike to arms, Tibullus may have found in the confusions of the time some means of evading or abridging his term of military service. Itis hard also to understand how he could have spent ten ol the hest years of his life in active campaigning without leaving a single indication of the fact in his poems: more especially as he has left us an ample record of his subsequent achievements in the train of his patron Messalla.

Of that distinguished man-M. Valerius Messalla Corvinus-a short account is given in the note to Tib. 1. 1. 53. Not less distinguished in literature than in politics, he had originally been a warm supporter of the Republican cause, and only passed over to the side of Octavianus about the year 37 or 36 Β. c. At what period his friendship for Tibullus began, we know not: hut he was doubtless attracted to him through admiration for his poetry, and he became his firm friend and patron through life. ln the commencement of the year Β. c. 31 (see 1. 1.) we find him inviting Tibullus to form part of his suite in the campaign which culminated in the battle of Actium. ln the autumn of the same year, Messalla was despatched by Octavianus to put down a rebellion amongst the Gauls of Aquitania: Tibullus accompanied him throughout the campaign, and in the seventh Elegy of the F irst Book has lelt'a vivid account of the tribes and the places which he saw during its progress. Towards the end of B.c. 30, Messalla was invested hy Augustus with ageneral commission to establish the affairs of the East (see Introd. to 1. 3): Tibullus again accompanied him, but falling sick at Corcyra, was left behind, and was unable to rejoin his patron. lt was during his illness on this occasion that he composed the despondent but beautiful poem r. 3.
